* ============================================================
*  PINOCCHIO SCALE -- DESTRUCTIVE VERB BATTERY (Phase 1.3b, v2 diagnostic)
*
*  Status:  CANDIDATE / REVIEW_BEFORE_EXECUTION. MUTATING (scratch clone only).
*  Safety:  Operates ONLY on a disposable clone (SCR_DESTR), built by COPY TO
*           from STUDENTS and ERASEd at the end. The pinocchio fixtures
*           (STUDENTS, ENROLL) are only READ (COPY source) and never mutated, so
*           their CDX/LMDB cannot desync and NO lane rebuild is required.
*
*  WHY v2 (finding from the v1 run, 2026-07-18):
*    v1 deleted a ~500,000-row range under the active CDX order and did NOT
*    finish in ~24 minutes (with TALK OFF, so it was real per-row work, not
*    console spam). Cause: DELETE refreshes the cursor position in the active
*    order per row, and that reposition uses the SAME linear index walk that
*    makes SEEK O(scan-distance) -- so DELETE-under-active-order is ~O(n^2).
*    v2 therefore uses SMALL (~10k) delete sets that complete, and A/B-tests
*    DELETE with the CDX order ACTIVE vs the order cleared (SET ORDER TO
*    PHYSICAL, which also closes the index) to quantify the CDX-involvement cost.
*
*    Clean timings we already have from v1: COPY TO (1M) = 84.1 s;
*    BUILDLMDB (1M, 1 tag) = 18.0 s.
*
*  RUNTIME: a few minutes (small delete sets; COPY/BUILDLMDB/PACK are the only
*    full-1M passes). Each command's ELAPSED (SET TIMER ON) is the datum.
*
*  RUN (host):
*    powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\dottalkpp\data\scripts\pinocchio\run_pinocchio_destructive_teed.ps1
* ============================================================
SET ECHO OFF
SET TIMER ON
* TALK OFF: bulk verbs would otherwise echo a per-row "Recno:" line (~thousands),
* flooding the console and making the elapsed console-I/O-bound. COUNT/SMARTLIST
* still print, which is all the canaries need.
SET TALK OFF

SET PATH DBF DBF/pinocchio
SET PATH INDEXES INDEXES/pinocchio
SET PATH LMDB LMDB/pinocchio

* ------------------------------------------------------------
* Startup cleanup: drop any SCR_DESTR left by an aborted run so CDX CREATE is
* fresh. Harmless "not found" if absent (runner reports and continues). If a
* stale SCR_DESTR.cdx / .cdx.d survives, BUILDLMDB CLEAN below rebuilds anyway.
* ------------------------------------------------------------
CLOSE
ERASE TABLE SCR_DESTR CONFIRM

* ============================================================
* D0. Clone STUDENTS (1M) into the disposable scratch table (expect ~84 s)
* ============================================================
ECHO === D0. COPY TO clone (full 1M-row copy) ===
SELECT 0
USE STUDENTS
COPY TO SCR_DESTR AS X64 OVERWRITE
USE SCR_DESTR
ECHO --- D0a. clone COUNT must be 1000000, canary recno 1 = 50000000 Taylor Quinn ---
COUNT
GO TOP
SMARTLIST SID,LNAME,FNAME NEXT 1

ECHO === D1. build the scratch index: CDX + BUILDLMDB (expect ~18 s) ===
CDX CREATE
CDX ADDTAG SID
BUILDLMDB HUGE CLEAN YES
CDX TAGS

* ============================================================
* D2. DELETE diagnostic -- same ~10k range (SID > 50990000), two conditions
* ============================================================
ECHO === D2a. DELETE FOR under ACTIVE CDX order (per-row reposition = O(n) walk) ===
SET ORDER TO TAG SID
DELETE FOR SID > 50990000
COUNT DELETED
ECHO --- clear order (PHYSICAL) before RECALL so RECALL is not also O(n^2) ---
SET ORDER TO PHYSICAL
RECALL ALL
COUNT DELETED

ECHO === D2b. DELETE FOR with order CLEARED (SET ORDER TO PHYSICAL, index closed) ===
SET ORDER TO PHYSICAL
DELETE FOR SID > 50990000
COUNT DELETED
RECALL ALL
COUNT DELETED
ECHO --- compare D2a vs D2b ELAPSED: the gap is the CDX-order reposition cost ---

* ============================================================
* D3. REINDEX CDX -> full index rebuild, data intact (expect ~18 s)
* ============================================================
ECHO === D3. REINDEX CDX CLEAN (rebuild the index over 1M rows) ===
REINDEX CDX CLEAN
CDX TAGS

* ============================================================
* D4. PACK -> mark ~10k (order cleared = fast), then rewrite the DBF
* ============================================================
ECHO === D4. PACK (DBF rewrite dropping deleted rows), full 1M pass ===
SET ORDER TO PHYSICAL
DELETE FOR SID > 50990000
COUNT DELETED
PACK
ECHO --- D4a. reopen after PACK; COUNT should be ~990001 (deleted rows gone) ---
USE SCR_DESTR
COUNT

* ============================================================
* D5. ZAP -> truncate to zero records (header rewrite, expected O(1))
* ============================================================
ECHO === D5. ZAP (truncate all rows), expected O(1) ===
ZAP
COUNT

* ============================================================
* D6. Cleanup: close and ERASE the scratch table (fixtures untouched)
* ============================================================
ECHO === D6. cleanup: ERASE SCR_DESTR ===
CLOSE
ERASE TABLE SCR_DESTR CONFIRM

ECHO ============================================================
ECHO DESTRUCTIVE DIAGNOSTIC COMPLETE. Confirm and record:
ECHO   D0 : clone COUNT = 1000000, canary recno 1 = 50000000 Taylor Quinn.
ECHO   D2a: DELETE FOR (~9999 rows) under ACTIVE order -- record ELAPSED.
ECHO   D2b: DELETE FOR (~9999 rows) order CLEARED -- record ELAPSED.
ECHO        D2a >> D2b confirms DELETE's per-row reposition is the O(n) walk.
ECHO   COUNT DELETED after each DELETE ~= 9999; after each RECALL ALL = 0.
ECHO   D3 : REINDEX CDX CLEAN ELAPSED (full rebuild).
ECHO   D4 : PACK ELAPSED (full DBF rewrite); reopened COUNT ~= 990001.
ECHO   D5 : ZAP ELAPSED (expected O(1)); COUNT = 0.
ECHO   NOTE: if ERASE leaves SCR_DESTR.cdx / SCR_DESTR.cdx.d behind, remove those
ECHO   sidecars from INDEXES/pinocchio and LMDB/pinocchio manually.
ECHO ============================================================
